  "slug": "jurassic-world-rebirth-does-not-find-a-way-plus-nolans-the-o",
  "title": "‘Jurassic World Rebirth’ Does Not Find a Way. Plus: Nolan’s ‘The Odyssey’ Is Coming!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2025-07-02",
  "runtimeMin": 92,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Chris Ryan break down the teaser for Christopher Nolan's 'The Odyssey,' then split three ways on 'Jurassic World Rebirth' after an 8 a.m. screening. Sean closes with an interview with Eva Victor about her debut, 'Sorry, Baby.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Nolan's 'The Odyssey' teaser and the summer trailers",
      "note": "seen before the Jurassic screening",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Odyssey",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The teaser leaked the day before; Amanda skipped it to see it in Dolby. Shot on IMAX 65mm: horses on the beach, the Trojan horse. John Leguizamo narrates ('Zeus's law smashed to pieces'), Tom Holland is a teary Telemachus, Jon Bernthal appears, and Matt Damon's Odysseus is seen only from behind and floating on a raft, never speaking. The cast plays it in nondescript American accents. Out one year to the month."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Running Man",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Edgar Wright's adaptation, with Glen Powell going bigger and angrier than usual opposite Josh Brolin, and Colman Domingo as the host. Same stairway/electrified-water-gun set-piece energy the hosts saw at CinemaCon; out November 7."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sentimental Value",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Sean is ready to be moved and skipped the trailer entirely; he just replied to the email asking when he could see it. Also opens November 7."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Jurassic World Rebirth'",
      "note": "Gareth Edwards · seventh in the franchise",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Jurassic World Rebirth",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The seventh Jurassic film and the fourth of the non-Spielberg era, directed by Gareth Edwards from a David Koepp script, with Scarlett Johansson as mercenary Zora Bennett, Mahershala Ali as boat captain Duncan Kincaid, Jonathan Bailey as a paleontologist, and Rupert Friend for the InGen spin-off chasing dinosaur DNA (land, sea, and air) to cure heart disease. Shot on film by John Mathieson; score by Alexandre Desplat. Chris had a good time and rated the craft; Amanda was moved by the wonder and the theme cues; Sean was mad: two disconnected movies (the mercenary mission and a family sailing through a 'dinosaur militarized zone') stapled together, a shot-for-shot rerun of the first film that insults the audience and never kills anyone. Praised set pieces: the mosasaurus/great-white water attack, the T. rex on its back, the pterodactyl grabbing raptors mid-piss. Chris ranks it fourth in the series; reviews landed at 53% on Rotten Tomatoes."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation with Eva Victor",
      "note": "her debut feature",
      "guest": "Eva Victor on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sorry, Baby",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Victor wrote, directed, and stars in her debut, made with Barry Jenkins's Pastel after a decade of rejection and years of one-minute comedy videos online. The nonlinear structure moves back four years and works toward the present, skipping the one it withholds; the film is built around a bathtub scene between Agnes and Lydie. She fought sepia-toned flashback conventions and 'Save the Cat' structure; the film was bought at Sundance for far more than it cost."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
